1. Windows Server VM(s) in Proxmox
Create the first Windows Server VM
Log in to Proxmox Web UI
In the top right, click Create VM
Under General
Choose your node
VM ID: leave default or choose one
Name: DC1 or Main-DC
Under OS
Select your Windows Server ISO
Under System
Leave default unless you want UEFI
Under Disks
Set disk size, for example 80 GB or more
Storage: choose your datastore
Under CPU
Select 2–4 cores
Under Memory
Set 4096 MB or more
Under Network
Choose bridge, usually vmbr0
Click Finish
Start the VM
Select the VM from the left panel
Click Start
Click Console
Go through normal Windows Server installation
Set local Administrator password
Rename the server
Inside Windows Server, open Server Manager
Click Local Server
Next to Computer name, click the current name
In System Properties, click Change
Rename it to DC1
Click OK
Restart
Set static IP
Open Server Manager
Click Local Server
Click the Ethernet link next to your network
In Network Connections, right-click adapter → Properties
Double-click Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4)
Enter:
IP address
Subnet mask
Default gateway
Preferred DNS = the server itself once DC is installed, or temporary DNS for now
Click OK


2. Active Directory Users and Computers
Install Active Directory Domain Services
Open Server Manager
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features
Click Next
Choose Role-based or feature-based installation
Select your server
Check Active Directory Domain Services
Click Add Features
Click Next until Install
Click Install
Promote server to Domain Controller
After installation, in Server Manager, click the notification flag
Click Promote this server to a domain controller
Choose Add a new forest
Enter root domain name, for example:
lab.local
Click Next
Set DSRM password
Keep DNS and Global Catalog checked
Continue through warnings
Click Install
Server restarts automatically
Open Active Directory Users and Computers
Open Server Manager
Click Tools
Click Active Directory Users and Computers

You will now see your domain and default containers.



3. OUs: IT, HR, Sales, Operations
Create Organizational Units
In Active Directory Users and Computers
Expand your domain name
Right-click the domain
Click New → Organizational Unit
Enter name: IT
Click OK
Repeat for:
HR
Sales
Operations
Optional: create users inside each OU
Right-click the OU, for example HR
Click New → User
Enter first name, last name, user logon name
Click Next
Set password
Choose password options
Click Finish

Repeat for each department.



4. Group Policy Management
Open Group Policy Management
Open Server Manager
Click Tools
Click Group Policy Management
Create a GPO for HR
Expand:
Forest
Domains
your domain
Right-click the HR OU
Click Create a GPO in this domain, and Link it here
Name it something like:
HR Policy
Click OK
Edit the GPO
Right-click HR Policy
Click Edit

Now configure the settings you want.

Password Policy

Important: domain password policy is usually applied at the domain level, not a normal OU GPO.

To set domain password policy:

In Group Policy Management
Right-click Default Domain Policy
Click Edit
Go to:
Computer Configuration
Policies
Windows Settings
Security Settings
Account Policies
Password Policy
Configure:
Minimum password length
Maximum password age
Password complexity
Close editor
No Control Panel Access

For OU-level users:

Edit HR Policy
Go to:
User Configuration
Policies
Administrative Templates
Control Panel
Double-click Prohibit access to Control Panel and PC settings
Set to Enabled
Click Apply → OK
Wallpaper Policy
In the same GPO editor, go to:
User Configuration
Policies
Administrative Templates
Desktop
Desktop
Double-click Desktop Wallpaper
Set to Enabled
Enter path to wallpaper file, for example a shared path
Choose style
Click Apply → OK
Mapped Drives
In GPO editor, go to:
User Configuration
Preferences
Windows Settings
Drive Maps
Right-click blank area → New → Mapped Drive
Action: Create
Location: \\DC1\HRShare
Drive Letter: choose one, e.g. H:
Label as: HR Shared Drive
Click Apply → OK

Repeat similar GPOs for Sales and Operations.

Force policy update
On client machine, open Command Prompt
Run:
gpupdate /force



5. Mapped Drives

This is often done after creating file shares.

Create a shared folder
Open File Explorer
Create folder, for example:
D:\HRShare
Right-click folder → Properties
Go to Sharing
Click Advanced Sharing
Check Share this folder
Give share name:
HRShare
Click Permissions
Remove broad access if needed
Add appropriate group or users
Click OK
Link it with GPO Drive Maps

Follow the mapped drives section above and point to:

\\DC1\HRShare
\\DC1\SalesShare
\\DC1\OperationsShare
Verify on client
Log in as a domain user from that OU
Open This PC
Check if mapped drive appears


6. FSRM quotas / file screening
Install FSRM
Open Server Manager
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features
Click Next
Select your server
Go to File and Storage Services
Expand File and iSCSI Services
Check File Server Resource Manager
Click Install
Open FSRM
In Server Manager
Click Tools
Click File Server Resource Manager
Create a quota
In FSRM, expand Quota Management
Click Quotas
On the right, click Create Quota
Select path, for example:
D:\HRShare
Choose:
Create quota on path
Select Derive properties from this quota template or define custom properties
Example size:
2 GB or 5 GB
Configure thresholds
85%
95%
100%
Add email or event notifications if you want
Click Create
Create file screening
In FSRM, expand File Screening Management
Click File Screens
On the right, click Create File Screen
Select folder path, e.g. D:\HRShare
Choose:
Active screening
Select template like Block Executable Files
or create custom screening group
Click Create
Exclude images/videos if you want
Under File Screening Management
Click File Groups
Create or edit a group
Add patterns like:
*.jpg
*.png
*.mp4
*.avi
*.exe
Use that group in your file screen



7. File permission settings

There are two layers:

Share permissions
NTFS permissions

NTFS is the more important one for fine control.

Set NTFS permissions
Right-click folder, e.g. D:\HRShare
Click Properties
Go to Security
Click Edit
Click Add
Add a user or group, for example:
HR Users
Select the group
Tick required permissions:
Read
Write
Modify
Click Apply → OK
Best practice setup

Example:

HR users → Modify
IT admins → Full control
Sales users → No access to HR share
Set Share permissions
Right-click folder → Properties
Go to Sharing
Click Advanced Sharing
Click Permissions
Remove Everyone if needed
Add specific groups
Assign:
Read
Change
Full Control
Click OK


8. Secondary Domain Controller

This is your backup/additional DC.

Create second Windows Server VM

In Proxmox:

Click Create VM
Name it DC2
Install Windows Server the same way
Assign static IP
Rename machine to DC2
Join DC2 to domain
On DC2, open Server Manager
Click Local Server
Click current Workgroup
Click Change
Choose Domain
Enter your domain name, e.g. lab.local
Enter domain admin credentials
Click OK
Restart
Install AD DS on DC2
Open Server Manager
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features
Install Active Directory Domain Services
After install, click notification flag
Click Promote this server to a domain controller
Add as additional domain controller
Choose Add a domain controller to an existing domain
Enter domain admin credentials if needed
Select your domain
Keep:
DNS checked
Global Catalog checked
Continue through wizard
Click Install
Server restarts
Verify replication
On DC1 or DC2, open Active Directory Users and Computers
Create a test user in an OU
Wait a bit
Check if it appears on the other DC
Check AD Sites and Services
Open Server Manager
Click Tools
Click Active Directory Sites and Services
Expand Servers
Verify both DC1 and DC2 appear

Important note:
What you built is usually redundancy/failover through AD replication, not a traditional Windows failover cluster for Domain Controllers. 

That is more correct.


9. WSUS dashboard
Install WSUS
Open Server Manager
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features
Select Windows Server Update Services
Add required features
Continue
Choose content location, for example:
D:\WSUS
Click Install
Post-install tasks
After installation, click the notification flag
Click Launch Post-Installation tasks
Wait until complete
Open WSUS
Open Server Manager
Click Tools
Click Windows Server Update Services
Initial WSUS configuration
In WSUS console, start configuration wizard
Choose whether to join Microsoft Update Improvement Program
Select upstream source:
Synchronize from Microsoft Update
Set proxy if needed
Choose:
Languages
Products
Classifications
Set sync schedule
Finish wizard
Click Synchronize Now


10. WDS deployment screen
Install WDS
Open Server Manager
Click Manage → Add Roles and Features
Select Windows Deployment Services
Install both:
Deployment Server
Transport Server
Click Install
Open WDS
Open Server Manager
Click Tools
Click Windows Deployment Services
Configure WDS
In the WDS console, expand server
Right-click your server
Click Configure Server
Choose Integrated with Active Directory
Set remote install folder path, for example:
D:\RemoteInstall
Choose PXE response option
Finish
Add boot image
Expand server
Right-click Boot Images
Click Add Boot Image
Browse to Windows ISO contents, usually:
sources\boot.wim
Name it
Finish
Add install image
Right-click Install Images
Create image group
Add install image from:
sources\install.wim
Finish
Test PXE boot
Create a test VM in Proxmox
Set network boot / PXE boot
Start VM
It should contact WDS and show deployment environment




Follow this exact order:

Create DC1 VM in Proxmox
Set static IP and rename server
Install AD DS and promote to DC
Open ADUC and create OUs
Create users/groups
Create shared folders
Set NTFS/share permissions
Create mapped drives through GPO
Install and configure FSRM
Install and configure WSUS
Install and configure WDS
Enable Data Deduplication
Create DC2
Join DC2 to domain
Promote DC2 as additional DC
Test login, replication, and access
